ğŸ”° Angular Beginner Topics â€” Real-Time Interview Q&A with Code Snippets

âœ… 1. Angular Basics
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhy is Angular called a framework and not just a library like React?â€

âœ… Answer:
Angular is called a framework because it provides:
* Opinionated structure (folders, modules, CLI)
* Built-in tools (Routing, HTTP, Forms, DI, Testing)
* Two-way binding, RxJS, and dependency injection out of the box
In contrast, React is a library â€” for building UIs only â€” and needs external libraries for routing, state, etc.

âœ… 2. Components
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhat happens when you declare the same component in two different Angular modules?â€

âœ… Answer:
âŒ It throws a runtime error.â€¨A component can only belong to one module at a time.
Why?â€¨Angular uses declarative metadata to track ownership of components. Re-declaring causes confusion during compilation.
âœ… Best Practice:â€¨If the component is reused, move it to a SharedModule and export it.

âœ… 3. Data Binding
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhatâ€™s the difference between [value]="username" and [(ngModel)]="username"?â€

âœ… Answer:
Binding Type	Syntax	Purpose
Property Binding	[value]="username"	One-way: From TS â†’ HTML
Two-way Binding	[(ngModel)]="username"	Two-way: Sync between view and model
ğŸ”§ Code Example:
<!-- Property binding -->
<input [value]="username" />

<!-- Two-way binding -->
<input [(ngModel)]="username" />
username = 'Roy';





ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œWhich one is more efficient in terms of performance?â€
âœ… Answer:â€¨One-way binding is generally faster because two-way adds overhead of change detection and event handling.

âœ… 4. Structural Directives
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œHow does Angular handle *ngIf behind the scenes? What does the asterisk (*) actually do?â€

âœ… Answer:
*ngIf is syntactic sugar.â€¨Itâ€™s equivalent to writing a <ng-template> and inserting/removing elements dynamically.

ğŸ”§ Behind the Scenes:
<!-- Shorthand -->
<div *ngIf="isLoggedIn">Welcome!</div>

<!-- Desugared -->
<ng-template [ngIf]="isLoggedIn">
  <div>Welcome!</div>
</ng-template>

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œCan you combine *ngIf and *ngFor on the same element?â€
âŒ No. Angular doesnâ€™t allow multiple structural directives on the same element.â€¨âœ… Workaround: Wrap one inside another:
<ng-container *ngIf="showList">
  <div *ngFor="let item of items">{{ item }}</div>
</ng-container>

âœ… 5. Pipes
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œCan you give me a scenario where youâ€™d write a custom pipe instead of using a method in the component?â€

âœ… Answer:
A custom pipe is used when:
* The transformation is simple and reusable
* Itâ€™s used directly in the template
* It should be pure (no side effects)

ğŸ”§ Example: Capitalize First Letter Pipe
@Pipe({ name: 'capitalize' })
export class CapitalizePipe implements PipeTransform {
  transform(value: string): string {
    return value.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + value.slice(1);
  }
}
<!-- Usage -->
<p>{{ 'angular' | capitalize }}</p>

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œWhat is the difference between a pure and an impure pipe?â€
Type	When Called
Pure Pipe	Only when input changes
Impure Pipe	Called on every change detection run
âœ… 6. Services & Dependency Injection
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œHow does Angular know which version of a service to inject when it is provided in both a module and a component?â€

âœ… Answer:
Angular uses Hierarchical Dependency Injection.
* If a service is provided at component level, that instance is scoped to that component tree
* If provided in root, it's singleton across the app

ğŸ”§ Example:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class AuthService {}
@Component({
  providers: [AuthService]  // creates new instance here
})
export class DashboardComponent {}

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œHow would you make sure a service is a singleton in the entire app?â€
âœ… Use:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
â›” Avoid listing the service in providers[] of multiple modules/components.

âœ… 7. Modules
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œLetâ€™s say you create a SharedModule and import FormsModule there. Will it be available in the components of other modules that import SharedModule?â€

âœ… Answer:
âŒ No â€” unless you also export the FormsModule from SharedModule.

ğŸ”§ Correct Way:
@NgModule({
  imports: [FormsModule],
  exports: [FormsModule, CommonModule]
})
export class SharedModule {}

âœ… Now all modules that import SharedModule will get access to FormsModule.

