ğŸ” More Real-Time Interview Q&A on Angular Beginner Topics

âœ… Topic: Components (Advanced Use)

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"How would you call a method of a child component from the parent component?"

âœ… Answer:
Use @ViewChild() decorator in the parent to get a reference to the child component instance.

ğŸ”§ Code Example:
// child.component.ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `<p>Child Component</p>`
})
export class ChildComponent {
  sayHello() {
    alert("Hello from Child!");
  }
}
// parent.component.ts
export class ParentComponent implements AfterViewInit {
  @ViewChild(ChildComponent) childComp!: ChildComponent;

  ngAfterViewInit() {
    this.childComp.sayHello();
  }
}

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
"Can @ViewChild() access an element inside the template instead of a component?"
âœ… Yes, use ElementRef:
@ViewChild('myInput') inputRef!: ElementRef;
<input #myInput />

âœ… Topic: Data Binding (Trickier Concepts)

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"Can you implement two-way binding without using [(ngModel)]?"

âœ… Answer:
Yes, by manually combining [value] and (input).

ğŸ”§ Code Example:
<input [value]="username" (input)="username = $event.target.value" />
<p>{{ username }}</p>
username = '';
This is essentially what [(ngModel)] does under the hood.

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
"Why might you prefer manual binding over ngModel?"
âœ… When using Reactive Forms, manual control is preferred. Also, ngModel does not work in strict Reactive Form mode unless imported.

âœ… Topic: Structural Directives (ngIf, ngFor, ngSwitch)

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"What is trackBy in *ngFor, and why should we use it?"

âœ… Answer:
trackBy helps Angular optimize DOM rendering by tracking items by unique identifier (like id) instead of object references.
Without trackBy, Angular destroys and recreates DOM nodes when the array changes â€” even if just one item changes.

ğŸ”§ Code Example:
<li *ngFor="let item of items; trackBy: trackById">
  {{ item.name }}
</li>
trackById(index: number, item: any) {
  return item.id;
}

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
"What happens if I donâ€™t use trackBy in a long list?"
You may face:
* Poor performance
* DOM flickering
* Unnecessary component re-rendering

âœ… Topic: Attribute Directives

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"What is the difference between [ngClass] and class binding? Which one is better?"

âœ… Answer:
Feature	[ngClass]	class Binding
Supports logic	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
Takes object/array	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
ğŸ”§ Example:
<!-- Works with logic -->
<div [ngClass]="{ 'active': isActive, 'error': hasError }"></div>

<!-- Basic binding -->
<div [class.active]="isActive"></div>

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
"Can you create a custom attribute directive to highlight text?"

ğŸ”§ Custom Highlight Directive:
@Directive({
  selector: '[appHighlight]'
})
export class HighlightDirective {
  constructor(el: ElementRef) {
    el.nativeElement.style.backgroundColor = 'yellow';
  }
}
<p appHighlight>This will be highlighted</p>

âœ… Topic: Pipes (Custom + Built-In)

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"Letâ€™s say you have a list of names. Create a pipe to filter names containing a search keyword."

ğŸ”§ Code Example:
@Pipe({ name: 'filterName' })
export class FilterNamePipe implements PipeTransform {
  transform(names: string[], keyword: string): string[] {
    if (!keyword) return names;
    return names.filter(name => name.toLowerCase().includes(keyword.toLowerCase()));
  }
}
<input [(ngModel)]="searchText" />
<ul>
  <li *ngFor="let name of names | filterName:searchText">{{ name }}</li>
</ul>

âœ… Topic: Dependency Injection (DI)

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"Can you inject a service into another service? What are the use cases?"

âœ… Answer:
Yes, Angular supports service-to-service injection using the same DI system.
ğŸ”§ Example:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class LoggerService {
  log(msg: string) {
    console.log('LOG:', msg);
  }
}

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class UserService {
  constructor(private logger: LoggerService) {}

  fetchUser() {
    this.logger.log('Fetching user...');
  }
}

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
"If I provide the same service in both component and root, how many instances are created?"
âœ… Two separate instances â€” one global, one local (scoped to component).â€¨This is a common source of bugs.

âœ… Topic: Modules

ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
"Why do we need feature modules? Canâ€™t we build everything inside AppModule?"

âœ… Answer:
While technically possible, using only AppModule leads to:
* Monolithic structure
* Poor scalability
* Hard-to-maintain code
âœ… Feature modules allow:
* Code separation
* Lazy loading
* Better testing and maintainability

