ğŸ”¥ Beginner Angular Interview Q&A â€” Set 2

âœ… 1. Topic: Component Interaction
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œSuppose you want to access a DOM element like <input> from the component class. How would you do it?â€

âœ… Answer:
Use Angularâ€™s @ViewChild() with ElementRef to get a reference to native DOM elements.

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
<input #usernameInput type="text" />
<button (click)="logInput()">Log Input</button>
@ViewChild('usernameInput') inputElement!: ElementRef;

logInput() {
  console.log(this.inputElement.nativeElement.value);
}

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œWhat are the drawbacks of using ElementRef directly?â€
âœ… Direct DOM manipulation can:
* Bypass Angularâ€™s rendering
* Introduce security issues (XSS)
* Break SSR (server-side rendering)
âœ… Use Renderer2 for safer DOM manipulation.

âœ… 2. Topic: Custom Directive
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œHow would you create a directive that changes text color when the mouse hovers over an element?â€

âœ… Answer:
Use @Directive with HostListener and ElementRef.

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
@Directive({
  selector: '[appHoverHighlight]'
})
export class HoverHighlightDirective {
  constructor(private el: ElementRef) {}

  @HostListener('mouseenter') onMouseEnter() {
    this.el.nativeElement.style.color = 'red';
  }

  @HostListener('mouseleave') onMouseLeave() {
    this.el.nativeElement.style.color = '';
  }
}
<p appHoverHighlight>Hover me!</p>

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œWhy do we avoid using nativeElement in directives?â€
âœ… To maintain platform independence and avoid direct DOM manipulation.
âœ… Best practice is to use Renderer2 instead of ElementRef.

âœ… 3. Topic: Template Binding & Safe Navigation
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œYour API response is delayed. How do you safely bind nested properties without getting errors?â€

âœ… Answer:
Use the safe navigation operator (?.) in the template.

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
<p>{{ user?.profile?.name }}</p>
This prevents Angular from throwing undefined property errors before user is defined.

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œHow is this different from using ngIf?â€
âœ… *ngIf="user" can conditionally render, preventing the binding altogether.â€¨âœ… ?. lets the template show partial values without breaking.

âœ… 4. Topic: ng-template and Structural Directives
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhat is the use of <ng-template>? Can you show an example?â€

âœ… Answer:
<ng-template> is a placeholder for content thatâ€™s rendered conditionally or dynamically inserted later.

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
<ng-template [ngIf]="isLoggedIn">
  <p>Welcome back, user!</p>
</ng-template>
With shorthand:
<p *ngIf="isLoggedIn">Welcome back, user!</p>

ğŸ§  Follow-Up:
â€œCan you use ng-template with ngFor?â€
âœ… Yes:
<ng-template ngFor let-user [ngForOf]="users">
  <p>{{ user.name }}</p>
</ng-template>

âœ… 5. Topic: Built-in Pipes
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œYou need to display todayâ€™s date in MM/dd/yyyy format. How do you do that in Angular?â€

âœ… Answer:
Use the date pipe.

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
