ğŸ”¥ Angular Beginner Interview Q&A â€” Set 4

âœ… 1. Topic: ngClass vs [class]
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhat is the difference between [class], [class.className], and [ngClass]? Which one is better?â€

âœ… Answer:
Syntax	Description
[class]="'className'"	Binds full class string
[class.className]="true"	Adds class conditionally
[ngClass]="{active: isActive}"	Adds/removes multiple classes dynamically
ğŸ”§ Examples:
<!-- Static class -->
<div class="active"></div>

<!-- Conditional class -->
<div [class.active]="isActive"></div>

<!-- Multiple dynamic classes -->
<div [ngClass]="{ active: isActive, error: hasError }"></div>

<!-- Dynamic from string -->
<div [class]="dynamicClass"></div>

ğŸ§  Best Practice:
Use [ngClass] for complex or multi-class logic.â€¨Use [class.className] for simple conditions.

âœ… 2. Topic: Event Binding with Parameters
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œHow do you pass arguments to a method from the template event binding?â€

âœ… Answer:
Use the event binding syntax (event)="method(arg)".

ğŸ”§ Code Snippet:
<button (click)="handleClick('Hello', $event)">Click</button>
handleClick(message: string, event: Event) {
  console.log(message);  // Hello
  console.log(event);    // MouseEvent
}
âœ… You can pass both custom data and the event object.

âœ… 3. Topic: Event Modifiers in Angular
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œCan you prevent default form submission using Angular without writing JS code inside the method?â€

âœ… Answer:
Yes, use event modifiers like $event.preventDefault() inside the template.

ğŸ”§ Example:
<form (submit)="onSubmit($event)">
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
onSubmit(event: Event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // prevent full page reload
  console.log("Form submitted");
}
âœ… Angular doesnâ€™t have built-in modifiers like Vue â€” use standard DOM event handling.

âœ… 4. Topic: Property Binding to Boolean Attributes
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhy doesnâ€™t [disabled]="false" remove the disabled attribute in some cases?â€

âœ… Answer:
Angular sets/removes boolean attributes like disabled or checked based on truthy/falsy values.
If [disabled]="false", it removes the attribute.
But if you use it incorrectly with interpolation:
<button disabled="{{ false }}">Click</button> <!-- still disabled -->
Interpolation always converts to string: 'false' is truthy.
âœ… Use [disabled] for proper behavior.

âœ… 5. Topic: One-Way vs Two-Way Binding Performance
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhy is one-way binding considered better for performance than two-way binding?â€

âœ… Answer:
Two-way binding ([(ngModel)]) registers a listener and update mechanism for every input, triggering Angular's change detection cycle.
One-way binding ([value]) is lighter â€” updates only from model to view.
âœ… Use two-way only when both input and output are needed.

ğŸ”§ Comparison Example:
<!-- One-way -->
<input [value]="name" />

<!-- Two-way -->
<input [(ngModel)]="name" />
âœ… For large forms, prefer Reactive Forms for more control and performance.

âœ… 6. Topic: What If a Component Isn't Displaying?
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œYou created a component, but it's not showing up in the browser. What could be the reasons?â€

âœ… Answer:
Check the following:
1. Component is declared in the module
2. Component selector is used correctly in the template
3. Component has no syntax errors
4. Itâ€™s not hidden via ngIf or CSS
5. Module containing the component is imported into root module (if in separate module)

âœ… 7. Topic: What Are Template Reference Variables?
ğŸ’¬ Interviewer Asks:
â€œWhat are template reference variables in Angular and when would you use them?â€

âœ… Answer:
Theyâ€™re declared using #varName in the template and allow direct access to DOM elements or component instances.

ğŸ”§ Example:
<input #nameInput type="text" />
<button (click)="log(nameInput.value)">Log</button>
log(val: string) {
  console.log(val);
}
âœ… Also used to reference child components in the same template.

