Routing and Navigation

Absolutely! Here's a complete and updated guide to Angular Routing & Navigation, with:
âœ… Concept explanationâ€¨âœ… Real-world structureâ€¨âœ… Code snippetsâ€¨âœ… Visual navigation flowâ€¨âœ… Guards, parameters, 404, and more

ğŸš¦ What is Routing in Angular?
Routing in Angular allows you to navigate between different views or components in a single-page application (SPA) without reloading the page.
Angular uses the RouterModule to map URLs â†’ Components.

ğŸ“ Real-World Folder Structure
src/app/
 â”œâ”€â”€ app-routing.module.ts      ğŸ‘ˆ Routing config file
 â”œâ”€â”€ home/
 â”‚   â””â”€â”€ home.component.ts
 â”œâ”€â”€ about/
 â”‚   â””â”€â”€ about.component.ts
 â”œâ”€â”€ product/
 â”‚   â””â”€â”€ product.component.ts
 â””â”€â”€ not-found/
     â””â”€â”€ not-found.component.ts

âœ… Step-by-Step Routing Setup

1. Create Components (CLI)
ng generate component home
ng generate component about
ng generate component product
ng generate component not-found

2. Create Routing Module
ng generate module app-routing --flat --module=app

3. Define Routes â€“ app-routing.module.ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterModule, Routes } from '@angular/router';

import { HomeComponent } from './home/home.component';
import { AboutComponent } from './about/about.component';
import { ProductComponent } from './product/product.component';
import { NotFoundComponent } from './not-found/not-found.component';

const routes: Routes = [
  { path: '', redirectTo: 'home', pathMatch: 'full' }, // default route
  { path: 'home', component: HomeComponent },
  { path: 'about', component: AboutComponent },
  { path: 'product/:id', component: ProductComponent }, // dynamic route
  { path: '**', component: NotFoundComponent }          // 404 route
];

@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes)],
  exports: [RouterModule]
})
export class AppRoutingModule {}

4. Use <router-outlet> in app.component.html
<!-- app.component.html -->
<h1>Angular Routing Demo</h1>
<nav>
  <a routerLink="/home">Home</a> |
  <a routerLink="/about">About</a> |
  <a [routerLink]="['/product', 101]">Product 101</a>
</nav>

<router-outlet></router-outlet>

5. Access Route Parameters â€“ product.component.ts
import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
import { ActivatedRoute } from '@angular/router';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-product',
  template: `<h2>Product ID: {{ productId }}</h2>`
})
export class ProductComponent implements OnInit {
  productId: any;

  constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.productId = this.route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id');
  }
}

ğŸ§­ Navigation Programmatically
Example: Navigate on button click
import { Router } from '@angular/router';

constructor(private router: Router) {}

goToAbout() {
  this.router.navigate(['/about']);
}
<button (click)="goToAbout()">Go to About</button>

ğŸ” Route Guards (e.g., AuthGuard)
1. Create Guard
ng generate guard auth
2. Implement canActivate
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class AuthGuard implements CanActivate {
  canActivate(): boolean {
    const loggedIn = true; // Simulate auth check
    return loggedIn;
  }
}
3. Apply Guard in Routing
{ path: 'about', component: AboutComponent, canActivate: [AuthGuard] }

âš ï¸ Wildcard Route for 404
{ path: '**', component: NotFoundComponent }

ğŸ” Child (Nested) Routes
Example: /settings/profile or /settings/security
const routes: Routes = [
  {
    path: 'settings',
    component: SettingsComponent,
    children: [
      { path: 'profile', component: ProfileComponent },
      { path: 'security', component: SecurityComponent }
    ]
  }
];
In settings.component.html
<h2>Settings</h2>
<router-outlet></router-outlet>

ğŸ”„ Route Params vs Query Params
Route Param: /product/:id
* Use route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id')
Query Param: /product?id=123
this.route.snapshot.queryParamMap.get('id')

ğŸ¨ RouterLinkActive (for active tabs)
<a routerLink="/home" routerLinkActive="active-link">Home</a>
.active-link {
  font-weight: bold;
  color: blue;
}

âœ… Summary Table
Feature	Example	Description
Navigate to route	routerLink="/home"	Simple link
Dynamic param	/product/:id	Pass value in URL
Programmatic nav	router.navigate(['/about'])	Via TS
Guard	canActivate	Control access
Wildcard	**	404 route
Nested	children: []	Sub-routing
Outlet	<router-outlet>	Place where routed content shows
Active Class	routerLinkActive	Styling active links
âœ… Real-Time Scenario: Product Dashboard
1. home page â†’ welcome info
2. product/:id â†’ show product details
3. about page â†’ about company
4. 404 page â†’ for wrong URLs
