[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[             [[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[[        ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]             ]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

Perfect! Now, letâ€™s move on to the next intermediate topic:

âš¡ Intermediate Angular Interview â€” Topic 3: Lifecycle Hooks

Q1:
Interviewer:â€¨"Can you explain what Angular lifecycle hooks are and why they are important?"

Answer:
Lifecycle hooks are methods that Angular calls at specific points during a componentâ€™s lifecycleâ€”creation, update, and destruction. They allow developers to tap into these moments to run custom logic, like fetching data, cleanup, or reacting to changes.

Q2:
Interviewer:â€¨"What is the difference between ngOnInit and constructor in Angular components?"

Answer:
* The constructor is a TypeScript feature and runs when the component class is instantiated.
* ngOnInit is an Angular lifecycle hook called after Angular has fully initialized the componentâ€™s data-bound properties. Itâ€™s the recommended place for initialization logic that requires inputs to be set.

Q3:
Interviewer:â€¨"How does the ngOnChanges lifecycle hook work? Can you give an example?"

Answer:
ngOnChanges is called whenever Angular sets or resets data-bound input properties. It receives a SimpleChanges object that contains previous and current values of the inputs.

Code Snippet:
@Component({
  selector: 'child-comp',
  template: `...`
})
export class ChildComponent implements OnChanges {
  @Input() data!: string;

  ngOnChanges(changes: SimpleChanges) {
    if (changes['data']) {
      console.log('Previous:', changes['data'].previousValue);
      console.log('Current:', changes['data'].currentValue);
    }
  }
}

Q4:
Interviewer:â€¨"When would you use ngAfterViewInit versus ngAfterContentInit?"

Answer:
* ngAfterContentInit is called after Angular projects external content into the component (using <ng-content>).
* ngAfterViewInit is called after the componentâ€™s own view and child views have been initialized.
Use ngAfterViewInit when you need to interact with view children (e.g., @ViewChild), and ngAfterContentInit when dealing with content projected from a parent.

Q5:
Interviewer:â€¨"How do you use ngOnDestroy, and why is it important?"

Answer:
ngOnDestroy is called just before Angular destroys the component. Use it to clean up resources like unsubscribing from observables or detaching event handlers to prevent memory leaks.

Code Snippet:
export class MyComponent implements OnDestroy {
  private subscription = this.service.getData().subscribe();

  ngOnDestroy() {
    this.subscription.unsubscribe();
  }
}

